{{infobox ethnic group |group=Lebanese Surinamese people |image= |caption= |poptime= |regions= [[Paramaribo]] |langs= [[Dutch language|Dutch]]{{·}}[[Sranan Tongo]]{{·}}[[Arabic]]{{·}}[[French language|French]] |rels=Majority: [[Roman Catholicism]] |related= [[Lebanese diaspora]] }} '''Lebanese Surinamese people''' are [[Suriname]]se citizens of [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] origin or descent.
== History == The first Lebanese, Nicolas Karkabé, arrived in Suriname around 1890 and settled there. He began as a peddler in the countryside but became a wealthy merchant in only a short time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/binn011sran01_01/binn011sran01_01_0010.php|title=Sranan. Cultuur in Suriname|work=dbnl.org}}</ref> The next Lebanese, mostly [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronites]], arrived in the 1990s from [[French Guiana]]. Within [[Lebanon]] they originate from a specific region, [[Bsharri]], a small (agrarian based) village (Bazaoun). Within Suriname they entered the [[textile]] trade that they dominate at present. The modest migration to Suriname continues to this day and this small group of Lebanese expatriates now counts 500 members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suriname.nu/150alg/libanezen01.html|title=Libanezen|work=Suriname.nu}}</ref>
