'''Michael Alexander Kellie''' (24 March 1947 – 18 January 2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://louderthanwar.com/mike-kellie-ones-spooky-tooth-drummer-rip|title=Mike Kellie (The Only Ones, Spooky Tooth drummer) RIP - Louder Than War|date=19 January 2017|work=louderthanwar.com|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> was an English musician, composer and record producer.

In a career that spanned more than 50 years, Kellie was a member of the [[Rock music|rock]] bands [[The V.I.P.s (band)|the V.I.P.s]], [[Spooky Tooth]] and [[the Only Ones]]. He was also a prolific [[session musician]] and worked with [[the Who]] on the film soundtrack of [[Tommy (soundtrack)|''Tommy'']], [[Joe Cocker]], [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]], [[George Harrison]], [[Jerry Lee Lewis]], [[Peter Frampton]], the [[Bee Gees]]'s [[Maurice Gibb]], [[Gary Wright]], [[Johnny Thunders]], [[Luther Grosvenor]], [[Neil Innes]], [[Steve Gibbons (musician)|Steve Gibbons]], [[Chris Jagger]], [[Nanette Workman]], [[Sean Tyla]], [[Jim Capaldi]], [[Pat Travers]] and [[Andy Fraser]].

In 2014, Kellie released his debut solo album ''Music from The Hidden'', while still a member of the Only Ones. He died on 18 January 2017 following a short illness.

==Early career==
{{more citations needed|section|date=November 2017}}
Michael Alexander Kellie was born on 24 March 1947, in [[Birmingham]], England, into a non-musical family. As a child, he showed an early interest in rhythm, practising on a coal shuttle with hearth brushes to simulate a [[snare drum]]. In his teen years, he joined St. Michaels Youth Club band as a drummer. He later played at "The Track" at Tudor Grange Sports Centre in [[Solihull]]. On the basis of this work, he was invited by Brian "Monk" Ffinch to play with Wayne and the Beachcombers in Birmingham, which started his career as a professional musician.<ref name=Mike>{{citation|url=http://hostedatklick.com/feature/1600/Exclusive+interview+with+Mike+Kellie.htm|title=Exclusive interview with Mike Kellie|publisher=The Village Times|date=10 June 2013|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref>

In 1966, Kellie played in Birmingham in a band called the Locomotive with [[Chris Wood (rock musician)|Chris Wood]] of [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]], and later with [[The V.I.P.s (band)|the V.I.P.'s]] (later Art) in [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]].

Manager [[Chris Blackwell]] found a singer and organist from the New York Times band named [[Gary Wright]], added him to the line-up of Art and launched the band Spooky Tooth with Kellie, [[Greg Ridley]], Jimmy Henshaw, [[Keith Emerson]], [[Luther Grosvenor]] and [[Mike Harrison (musician)|Mike Harrison]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/1278548-VIPs-The-2|title=V.I.P.'s, The|publisher=Discogs|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref>

After the initial decline of Spooky Tooth, Kellie joined [[Johnny Hallyday]]'s band for a summer tour of France in 1974, before forming [[The Only Ones]] in 1976 with [[Peter Perrett]], [[Alan Mair]] and [[John Perry (musician)|John Perry]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://thebeaverdialogues.blogspot.com/2007/05/only-ones.html|title=The Only Ones|author=Perry, Kevin|date=1 May 2007|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref>

The Only Ones, possibly best known for the single "[[Another Girl, Another Planet]]", recorded three albums for [[Columbia Records|CBS]], although over time, their catalogue has contained many compilations and other releases, which now outnumber their [[studio album]]s.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}

In February 1978, [[Johnny Thunders]] moved to [[London]] with his family, and began playing with a loose revue dubbed the Living Dead.<ref>{{citation |url=https://punkmusiccatalogue.wordpress.com/living-dead|title=Living Dead|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> Kellie became part of this floating line-up (that also included Perrett along with various [[Sex Pistols]] including [[Steve Jones (musician)|Steve Jones]] and [[Paul Cook]]) and recorded Thunders’ ''[[So Alone (album)|So Alone]]'' album together with his signature song "[[You Can't Put Your Arms Around a Memory]]".

Following the Only Ones' farewell in 1981 at London's Lyceum, Kellie moved to the countryside north of [[Toronto]], Canada, where he spent four years away from performing.<ref name=Mike /> He used this time to learn the piano and write songs.

==Break from music and later career==
{{more citations needed|section|date=November 2017}}
Returning to Britain in 1985, Kellie spent several years hill farming in [[North Wales]] and [[Scotland]] where he became a shepherd. In 1999 Kellie reunited with Mike Harrison, Luther Grosvenor and Greg Ridley under the Spooky Tooth moniker. Together they released the ''[[Cross Purpose]]'' album.

In 2004, Kellie reunited with Mike Harrison and Gary Wright to play dates in Germany as a new incarnation of Spooky Tooth. The band later released the DVD ''Nomad Poets'' with live performances from [[Worpswede]] and [[Hamburg]], Germany.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.spookytooth.sk/nomad_poets.html|title=Nomad Poets|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref>

In 2007, the Only Ones reformed, touring the UK, Europe and Japan<ref>{{citation |work=Uncut|title=Peter Perrett’s Only Ones Set For Reunion Tour|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/news/peter-perrett-s-only-ones-set-for-reunion-tour-62969#2p06g2igmE5DgAJY.99|date=4 November 2011|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> as well as performing on BBC TV's ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]''.

In 2010, with the Only Ones undergoing another sabbatical, Kellie began recording his own collection of music which become his first solo album. Entitled ''Music from The Hidden'', the album was produced by Kellie who also played drums, organ, bass and acoustic guitars, percussion and sang lead vocals. There are also contributions from Gordon Jackson (acoustic guitar), Finley Barker and Tony Kelsey (guitars), [[Steve Winwood]] (organ, mandolin and bass), Bill Hunt, Levi French and Tony Ariss (pianos), Rob Harrison (bass) [[Steve Gibbons (musician)|Steve Gibbons]] (backing vocals) and Greg Platt Lake (guitar and vocals).<ref name=Mike/>

Kellie was prominent among the musicians featured on the six-CD ''Jess Roden Anthology'',<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.hiddenmasters.net/uncut-magazine-reviews-jess-rodens-anthology/|work=Uncut|title=Uncut magazine reviews Jess Roden’s Anthology|accessdate=25 August 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207083735/http://www.hiddenmasters.net/uncut-magazine-reviews-jess-rodens-anthology/|archivedate=7 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> presented by Hidden Masters.

He contributed to the 2011 sessions for the Distractions re-union album, ''The End of the Pier'',<ref>{{citation |url=http://recordcollectormag.com/reviews/the-end-of-the-pier|work=Record Collector|title=Distractions: End of the Pier|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> which was released on Occultation Records in 2012.

